In the OfficeA review of the emergency preparedness and response shall be carried out in Company’s office as follows:1) After the occurrence of an accident or emergency situation in which office emergency response team was activated.2) After conduct of an office ship/shore drill.The review shall include a de-briefing to discuss effectiveness of the emergency procedures, the lessons learnt and agreeimprovements [if any] to be made to the company’s emergency procedures. Points arising from such debriefings meetings should besummarized and kept with relevant drill record. These shall also be circulated to relevant staff within the organisation.The HSEQA Superintendent shall maintain records of these reviews. Actions requiring follow up shall be raised as ‘Observations’ and should include due date for completion. The HSEQA Superintendent isresponsible to ensure that corrective action is taken in good time8HANDLING INSURANCE MATTERSTechnical Department will handle all insurance matters. The following are the processes for handling various aspects of insurancematters:8.1P&I UNDERWRITERS8.1.1P&I AND FD&D CERTIFICATE OF ENTRY (COE)The P&I Certificate of Entry expires on the 20th of February of every year. Renewed policies are to be requested from Owners / P&Iclubs at least 1 month in advance. Regular follow-up will be required to ensure that the certificate is placed onboard before the expirydate. Upon receipt of the CoE, all information (ship’s details, Owner & ESM name, dates, etc) has to be checked before forwarding to theconcerned vessel.It is important to ensure that the Company is stated as the co-assured in the cover. This is required to protect Company’s interest incase of any claim.Due to present shipping practices it is mandatory to have valid and original P&I CoE onboard at all times. Most clubs send the CoE byemail at the time of renewals. These when printed in colour are accepted as originals. Vessels have to be advised on each suchoccasion. Originals will be issued by the Club upon request.If the Certificate of Entry is not ready, after agreeing to the new terms with the owner, the club then issues a Confirmation of Entry inthe interim which can be used till Certificate of Entry is issued.8.1.2WRECK REMOVAL CERTIFICATEThe Nairobi International Convention on the Removal of Wrecks, 2007, was adopted by an international conference held in Kenya in 2007. The Nairobi InternationalConvention on the Removal of Wrecks entered into force on Tuesday (14 April 2015).The Convention places strict liability on owners for locating, marking and removing wrecks deemed to be a hazard and makes Statecertification of insurance, or other form of financial security for such liability, compulsory for ships of 300 gt and above. It also providesStates Parties with a right of direct action against insurers.PnI club issues the "Blue Card for Wreck Removal" after which the application for issue of the "Wreck Removal Certificate" is made tothe administration.8.1.3P&I COVERThe P&I cover is usually arranged by the Owner, however, sometimes they may request the Company to arrange the cover. In suchcases the process is to be started about 2 months in advance and guidance sought from Senior Management before proceeding toobtain quotations. The clubs may be contacted directly for quotes or through brokers. They require certain ship specific informationlike GRT, Class, year of build, type of ship, etc in order to give their quotes.8.1.4P&I COVER FOR NEW JOINERS DURING TAKE OVERTechnical Department has to keep Crew dept informed of the name of the P&I club, so that the club can be notified by them and theP&I cover for the new joiners can be confirmed before our ship staff depart from their home country.8.2HULL AND MACHINERY UNDERWRITERSIt is important to ensure that the Company is stated as the co-assured in the cover.8.2.1INSURANCE POLICY FOR H&M, IV, WAR, LOHFor all ships whose policies are arranged by owners renewed policies are to be requested from Owners at least 2 weeks in advance.Regular follow-up will be required to ensure that the certificate is placed onboard before the expiry date. Usually photocopies are onlyprovided and this is sufficient. It is to be noted that it is not mandatory for H&M certificates to be placed on board, as in the case of P&Icertificates.8.2.2NOTIFICATION FOR BREACH OF WAR POLICYAs and when Joint War Committee (JWC) announces/ releases the Hull War, Strikes, Terrorism and Related Perils Listed Areas (thiscontains the list of war risk areas), it is updated in our company’s Technical circular, T3.
